 System Architecture Study Guide: From Beginner to Advanced

1. Beginner (Fundamentals)

 What is System Architecture?
System architecture is the high-level blueprint of how software components work together to solve a problem at scale. It defines structure, behavior, and interactions—not the code itself.

Real-world analogy: Think of building a city.  
- Code = bricks (individual buildings).  
- Architecture = city plan (roads, water supply, power grid, zoning laws).  
A good plan ensures the city grows without traffic jams, blackouts, or collapsing buildings. Poor architecture leads to chaos when the population grows.

Key insight: Architecture decisions made early (e.g., monolith vs microservices) are extremely expensive to change later.

 Goals of System Architecture (The "Non-Functional Requirements")
Every architecture decision must balance these five goals:

| Goal              | Definition                                                                 | Real-World Trade-off Example                  | Interview Question Hook                  |
|-------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------|
| Scalability   | Handle growth in users, data, or traffic without redesign                  | Instagram scaling from 1M to 1B users         | "How would you scale from 10k to 10M users?" |
| Availability  | System stays "up" (measured as uptime % – e.g., 99.99% = <52 min downtime/year) | Netflix never going down during peak hours    | "Design a system with 99.99% availability" |
| Maintainability | Easy to update, debug, and extend by new engineers                        | Facebook's move from monolith to microservices| "How do you reduce deployment time?"     |
| Security      | Protect data, prevent unauthorized access, and handle threats              | Equifax breach due to poor architecture       | "How do you secure API communication?"   |
| Cost          | Optimize infrastructure and operational expenses                           | Using spot instances vs always-on servers     | "How do you keep costs under $X/month?"  |

Pro tip: Always ask in interviews: "Which of these goals is most important for this system?"

 Architecture Views (The 4+1 View Model – simplified)
No single diagram shows everything. Use multiple views:

1. Logical View – What the system does (components, classes, relationships).
2. Physical View – Hardware mapping (servers, networks, data centers).
3. Data View – How data flows and is stored (databases, schemas).
4. Process View – Runtime behavior (threads, processes, communication).

C4 Model (best for interviews – explained in Section 6):
- C1: Context (high-level, people + systems).
- C2: Container (apps, databases, queues).
- C3: Component (inside a container).
- C4: Code (classes – rarely drawn in interviews).

 Client-Server Model & APIs
- Client-Server: Basic pattern where clients (browser, mobile app) request resources from servers.
  - Thick client (e.g., desktop apps) does heavy work locally.
  - Thin client (web apps) offloads work to server.
- APIs (Application Programming Interfaces): The "contract" between client and server.
  - REST: Stateless, uses HTTP methods (GET/POST), JSON. Most common for beginners.
  - GraphQL: Client specifies exactly what data it wants (avoids over-fetching).
  - gRPC: High-performance, uses Protocol Buffers (used by Google, Netflix).

Real-world example: Your phone (client) → Instagram API (server) → Database.

Interview tip: Always clarify: "Is this a mobile-first or web-first system?"

