 2. Core Concepts

 Servers: Evolution from Physical to Containers
- Physical Servers: Bare-metal machines. Expensive, slow to scale.
- Virtual Machines (VMs): Hypervisor (e.g., VMware) runs multiple OSes on one physical server. Each VM has its own kernel → still heavy.
- Containers (Docker): Lightweight virtualization. Shares host OS kernel. Starts in milliseconds.
  - Docker packages app + dependencies into immutable images.
  - Orchestration: Kubernetes manages thousands of containers (auto-scaling, self-healing).

Example: A monolith app on one VM vs. same app in 50 containers across a Kubernetes cluster.

 Networking Fundamentals
- IP: Every device gets a unique address (IPv4: 192.168.x.x).
- DNS: Phonebook of the internet (translates `twitter.com` → IP).
- Ports: Doors on a server (80=HTTP, 443=HTTPS).
- Reverse Proxy (e.g., NGINX): Sits in front of servers, handles SSL, load distribution, caching.
- CDN (Content Delivery Network): Edge servers worldwide that cache static content (images, CSS). Reduces latency.

Real-world: Cloudflare CDN caches Instagram images closer to users in Kolkata.

 Databases: The Heart of Any System
SQL vs NoSQL (critical comparison table):

| Aspect              | SQL (PostgreSQL, MySQL)                          | NoSQL (MongoDB, Cassandra)                     |
|---------------------|--------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------|
| Schema              | Fixed (tables, rows, columns)                    | Flexible (documents, key-value, graphs)        |
| Scaling             | Vertical (bigger machine) + some horizontal      | Horizontal (easy sharding)                     |
| Use Case            | Transactions, complex queries                    | High volume, unstructured data                 |
| Consistency         | Strong (ACID)                                    | Usually eventual (BASE)                        |

ACID vs BASE:
- ACID (SQL): Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability → Bank transfers.
- BASE (NoSQL): Basically Available, Soft state, Eventual consistency → Social media feeds.

Indexing & Normalization:
- Indexing: Like book index → speeds up searches (B-tree, Hash). But slows writes.
- Normalization: Reduce redundancy (1NF → 3NF). Trade-off: more JOINs = slower reads.
- Denormalization: Opposite – duplicate data for faster reads (common in NoSQL).

Example: E-commerce order table (SQL) vs. user activity logs (NoSQL).

