 6. Real-World System Design: Design Twitter/X (FAANG Classic)

Requirements (always clarify in interview):
- Post tweet (text + media).
- Timeline: Home + user timeline.
- Follow/unfollow.
- Scale to 500M users, 1M QPS peak.

High-Level Components (C4 Context):
- Clients → API Gateway + Load Balancer.
- Services: Tweet, Timeline, User, Media.
- Storage: Cassandra (tweets), Redis (cache), Kafka (events), S3 (media).

Key Design Decisions:
- Timeline Generation:
  - Fan-out on Write (push): When user posts, push to all followers' timelines (Redis lists). Good for read-heavy.
  - Fan-out on Read (pull): Generate timeline on-the-fly. Good for write-heavy or celebrities.
- Handling Celebrities (hot users with 100M followers):
  - Hybrid: Normal users = fan-out on write. Celebrities = fan-out on read + separate cache.
- Sharding:
  - Tweets sharded by tweet ID (snowflake) or user ID.
  - Consistent hashing to minimize reshuffling.
- Tech Stack:
  - Redis: Timeline cache, rate limiting.
  - Kafka: Async fan-out, notifications.
  - Cassandra: High write throughput for tweets.
  - Elasticsearch: Search.

Bottlenecks & Mitigations:
- Write spikes → Rate limiting + queuing.
- Read spikes → Heavy Redis + CDN for media.

Diagram Tip: Draw C2 (containers): Clients → LB → API Gateway → Services → (Redis, Kafka, DBs).

